\subsection{Vision-Language Models}
Vision-Language Models (VLMs) aim to learn unified representations over visual and textual modalities and to support cross-modal understanding and generation. Early work typically relied on contrastive or matching objectives to align image and text embeddings, which enabled strong performance on retrieval and classification tasks. More recent research has shifted toward large-scale generative training, where an image is encoded into visual tokens that are consumed by an autoregressive language model to produce open-ended text outputs, thereby enhancing instruction following and general-purpose visual reasoning ability.

\paragraph{InternVL series.}
The InternVL family represents a line of open-source VLMs that scale up multimodal pretraining and instruction tuning to build general-purpose vision-language assistants. InternVL models commonly adopt an image encoder (e.g., ViT-style backbones) together with a projection module that maps visual features into the token space of a large language model, enabling unified decoding for captioning, visual question answering, and multi-step reasoning. Through large-scale multimodal data and carefully designed training recipes, InternVL models have demonstrated competitive performance across a broad range of benchmarks, and provide practical baselines for both academic research and downstream applications.

\paragraph{Qwen-VL series.}
Qwen-VL is another representative open-source VLM line that emphasizes strong instruction-following, multilingual capability, and robust visual reasoning. Architecturally, Qwen-VL typically couples a vision encoder with a large language model and trains on diverse image-text pairs and instruction data. Beyond standard single-image understanding, Qwen-VL variants also explore capabilities such as grounding and fine-grained recognition, making them suitable for tasks requiring accurate reading of visual content (e.g., OCR-like understanding) and structured responses.

\paragraph{Beyond single-image captioning: interleaved data, multimodal reasoning, and video understanding.}
Recent Large Multimodal Models (LMMs) extend VLMs in three notable directions. First, training with \emph{interleaved} image-text sequences (rather than isolated image-caption pairs) improves long-context multimodal modeling and better matches real-world document and web data. Second, multimodal reasoning has become a central focus, where models are expected to perform compositional, multi-hop, and tool-augmented reasoning grounded in visual evidence, often under instruction-tuned settings. Third, video understanding introduces temporal dynamics and event-level reasoning, requiring models to aggregate information across frames and align it with textual descriptions or questions. These advances collectively push VLMs toward more general multimodal agents that can perceive, reason, and generate in complex real-world scenarios.
