```latex
\subsection{Visual Generative Models}
Visual generative models aim to synthesize high-fidelity images conditioned on diverse inputs such as text prompts, reference images, and editing instructions. In recent years, the dominant paradigm has shifted from early autoregressive generators to diffusion-based frameworks, where images are generated by iteratively denoising from Gaussian noise. Diffusion models have demonstrated strong scalability and sample quality, and have become the backbone of many text-to-image and image-editing systems. Beyond diffusion, alternative continuous-time generative paradigms have gained increasing attention, including flow-matching and rectified-flow style training, which learn a velocity/flow field to transport noise to data and can improve sampling efficiency and training stability. In parallel, discrete token generation remains an important direction: images are first compressed into discrete visual tokens (e.g., via VQ-style codecs) and then generated autoregressively by a language-model-like transformer, offering a unified token space and potentially better integration with LLMs, albeit often trading off fine details or requiring strong tokenizers and large-scale training.

\paragraph{Text-to-image generation.}
Recent large-scale text-to-image models continue to improve prompt fidelity, aesthetic quality, and controllability. Representative systems include commercial and open models such as SD~3.5, Hunyuan Image~3.0, and OmniGen~1/2, which emphasize stronger instruction following and more robust compositional generation. Meanwhile, the community has explored data-centric and architecture-centric approaches to improve rendering of complex structures and text, as well as generalization to long prompts and multi-concept descriptions.

\paragraph{Instruction-driven image editing.}
Image editing models extend generative capabilities to manipulate an existing image under a textual instruction while preserving non-target regions. Recent systems (e.g., FLUX-Kontext, Step-1X Edit) highlight the importance of (i) preserving identity and background details, (ii) enforcing localized modifications, and (iii) maintaining semantic coherence under structural changes such as pose or viewpoint edits. Compared with text-to-image generation, editing places stricter constraints on faithfulness to the input image, making high-quality paired data and reliable evaluation protocols particularly critical.

\paragraph{Recent large multimodal generators.}
A line of large multimodal generative models integrates powerful language backbones with image generation or editing modules, aiming for unified instruction following across modalities. Examples include Ovis-Image, LongCat-Image, Qwen-Image, and Z-Image, which generally focus on improving prompt compliance, multilingual text rendering, and context-aware editing. In addition, Query-Kontext and related Kontext-style methods explore query-conditioned generation/editing with stronger controllability over local content and layout. The SANA series and DreamOmni2 further investigate scalable training and general-purpose generation under diverse conditions. Overall, these efforts suggest a trend toward building more general visual generation systems that support long-form prompts, precise text rendering, and robust instruction-based editing.
